Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @Yukon Gold Potatoes{12%ounce} into 1⁄2-inch-thick wedges. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens; finely chop whites until you have 1 TBSP (2 TBSP for 4 servings). Finely chop @chili pepper{1}. Trim, peel, and grate @carrot{3%ounce} on the largest holes of a #box grater{}; place in a #medium bowl{}.

> Trim broccoli florets if necessary.

Toss potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%teaspoon}, @salt{} and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack until golden brown and crispy, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{}, combine @mayonnaise{2%tablespoon}, @Dijon mustard{2%teaspoon}, 1 TBSP scallion whites, 1 tsp white wine vinegar, and a pinch of chili to taste. (You'll use the rest of the sour cream and vinegar later.) Season with salt and pepper. Set aside.

> Swap in broccoli for potatoes.

To bowl with carrot, add @shredded red cabbage{4%ounce}, remaining vinegar, 2 TBSP scallion greens (4 TBSP for 4 servings), two packets @sour cream{1/2%cup}, and @sugar{1.5%teaspoon}. (You'll use the rest of the sour cream in the next step.) Season with a big pinch of salt and pepper; toss to combine.

Halve @tilapia{11%ounce} fillets lengthwise (you'll have a larger piece and a smaller piece). Pat dry with #paper towels{}. In a #shallow dish{}, combine @OLD BAY® seasoning{1%unit}, remaining sour cream, and 1 TBSP water. On a #plate{}, combine @panko breadcrumbs{1/2%cup} and @cornstarch{1%tablespoon}. Dip each fillet into sour cream mixture, then press into panko mixture, coating all over.

Heat a 1⁄3-inch layer of oil in a large, preferably nonstick, pan over medium-high heat. Once oil is hot enough that a pinch of panko mixture sizzles when added to the pan, add tilapia. (For 4 servings, fry fish in batches.) Cook until crust is golden and fish is cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes} per side. (The smaller pieces will cook faster.) Transfer to a paper-towel-lined plate.

Divide tilapia, slaw, and @broccoli florets{8%ounce} between plates. Serve with remoulade. Garnish with any remaining scallion greens.